      <section id="conclusion">
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>Cognitive biases cannot be eliminated — they are features of human cognition that evolved for good reasons in different environments. What can be reduced is their impact on consequential decisions, through structural changes to how those decisions are made. The most effective approach combines pre-commitment, the outside view, deliberate search for disconfirming evidence, and pre-mortem analysis. Applied consistently, these tools don't make you immune to bias — they make you less systematically wrong in the decisions that matter most.</p>

        <ContentBox type="tip" title="Start Here">
          Pick the one bias that costs you most — for most people, it's overconfidence or confirmation bias. Design one structural fix for your next major decision: an outside view check, a devil's advocate session, or a formal pre-mortem. Build from there.
        </ContentBox>
      </section>

